Time Model Statistics

  • DB Time represents total time in user calls
  • DB CPU represents CPU time of foreground processes
  • Total CPU Time represents foreground and background processes
  • Statistics including the word "background" measure background process time, therefore do not contribute to the DB time statistic
  • Ordered by % of DB time in descending order, followed by Statistic Name

ROUND(100 * (GREATEST(MA.SUM_IO_UNC_BYTES, MA.SUM_IO_ELIG_BYTES) - MA.SUM_IO_RET_BYTES) / MA.SUM_IO_ELIG_BYTES, 2))) END) ) END) FROM MONITOR_AGG MA) ELSE NULL END) FROM (SELECT CASE WHEN V1.XPLAN_XML IS NULL OR V1.XPLAN_XML.EXISTSNODE('/error') > 0 THEN NULL ELSE V1.XPLAN_XML END XPLAN_XML FROM (SELECT CASE WHEN :B36 = 1 THEN DBMS_XPLAN.BUILD_PLAN_XML( TABLE_NAME=>'gv$all_sql_plan', 8zu93vh45zc30 with alter_roles as ( select role from role_sys_privs where privilege = :PRIV1 ), tc_roles as ( select role from alter_roles union select role from role_role_privs start with granted_role in (select role from alter_roles) connect by granted_role = prior role ) select sum(cnt) privs from ( select count(*) cnt from user_tab_privs where owner = :OWNER and table_name = :NAME and privilege = :"SYS_B_0" union all select count(*) from user_sys_privs where privilege = :PRIV1 union all select count(*) from all_tab_privs where GRANTOR = :OWNER and table_name = :NAME and privilege = :"SYS_B_1" and grantee = :"SYS_B_2" union all SELECT count(:"SYS_B_3") FROM user_role_privs WHERE granted_role IN (select role from tc_roles) )

9u3y1y5mh10kpselect NULL ENTRY, inner.* from ( select null name, -:"SYS_B_00" LINE, -:"SYS_B_01" COL, null USAGE, case when obj.object_type like :"SYS_B_02" then :"SYS_B_03" else obj.object_type end TYPE, OWNER, case when obj.object_type like :"SYS_B_04" then :"SYS_B_05" else obj.object_type end OBJECT_TYPE, obj.OBJECT_NAME from sys.all_objects obj where rownum <= :"SYS_B_06" and obj.object_type != :"SYS_B_07" and obj.object_type != :"SYS_B_08" and obj.object_type != :"SYS_B_09" and object_name like :object_name and object_type in ( :1, :2, :3 ) and owner in ( :4, :"SYS_B_10" ) ) inner where rownum <= :"SYS_B_11" order by case when OWNER = SYS_CONTEXT(:"SYS_B_12", :"SYS_B_13") then :"SYS_B_14 " else OWNER end, type, CASE WHEN USAGE = :"SYS_B_15" OR USAGE = :"SYS_B_16" THEN :"SYS_B_17" ELSE :"SYS_B_18" END, usage, object_name, line, col, name

  • Top SQL statements by DB Time along with the top events by DB Time for those SQLs.
  • % Activity is the percentage of DB Time due to the SQL.
  • % Event is the percentage of DB Time due to the event that the SQL is waiting on.
  • % Row Source is the percentage of DB Time due to the row source for the SQL waiting on the event.
  • Executions is the number of executions of the SQL that were sampled in ASH.

          Findings and Recommendations
          ----------------------------
 
Finding 1: Commits and Rollbacks
Impact is 8.32 active sessions, 33.8% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Waits on event "log file sync" while performing COMMIT and ROLLBACK operations 
were consuming significant database time.
 
   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is 8.33 active sessions, 33.8% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic for possible reduction in the number of 
      COMMIT operations by increasing the size of transactions.
   Rationale
      The application was performing 141402 transactions per minute with an 
      average redo size of 5073 bytes per transaction.
 
   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is 8.33 active sessions, 33.8% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the possibility of improving the performance of I/O to the 
      online redo log files.
   Rationale
      The average size of writes to the online redo log files was 15 K and the 
      average time per write was 1 milliseconds.
   Rationale
      The total I/O throughput on redo log files was 10 M per second for reads 
      and 24 M per second for writes.
   Rationale
      The redo log I/O throughput was divided as follows: 0% by RMAN and 
      recovery, 70% by Log Writer, 0% by Archiver, 0% by Streams AQ and 29% by 
      all other activity.
 
   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Commit" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 8.33 active sessions, 33.8% of total activity.

Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
The throughput of the I/O subsystem was not significantly lower than expected.
 
   No recommendations are available.

Impact is 3.7 active sessions, 15.01% of total activity.

"Cluster" waits were found.
 
   Recommendation 1: Segment Tuning
   Estimated benefit is 1.32 active sessions, 5.37% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------

      object ID 96401.

Finding 5: Shared Pool Latches
Impact is .83 active sessions, 3.36% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Contention for latches related to the shared pool was consuming significant 
database time.
Waits for "library cache: mutex X" amounted to 2% of database time.
 
   No recommendations are available.
 
   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Concurrency" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .89 active sessions, 3.63% of total activity.
 
 
Finding 6: Soft Parse
Impact is .7 active sessions, 2.83% of total activity.
------------------------------------------------------
Soft parsing of SQL statements was consuming significant database time.
 
   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .7 active sessions, 2.83% of total activity.
   -----------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic to keep open the frequently used cursors. 
      Note that cursors are closed by both cursor close calls and session 
      disconnects.
 
   Recommendation 2: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .7 active sessions, 2.83% of total activity.
   -----------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Consider increasing the session cursor cache size by increasing the 
      value of parameter "session_cached_cursors".
   Rationale
      The value of parameter "session_cached_cursors" was "50" during the 
      analysis period.
